## Explanation:

We are planning to build a Flutter payment processing module which will have in-app purchases and mobile wallet integration. It's primary goal is to reduce integration effort required with the existing legacy iOS and Android modules. The Flutter platform offers native UI elements like CupertinoButton, and CupertinoTextField. We will use these elements for the input fields. These widgets are available as plugins from Google in their official flutter plugin repository.

We will use third party mobile wallets for making payment. In our case we need to support both Amex, Visa and Mastercard. As of now there is no native SDK for this. To achieve this, we are planning to create a custom flutter module. The main idea behind the flutter module is to present a custom UI for entering the card number and other fields like CVV. Once the user submits these details then we will hit the merchant's backend server with these details and return the payment ID in response which is used by our Flutter app to verify and confirm payment transactions. To handle this, we are planning to use webview_flutter plugin which basically allows us to open and load an URL for a given URL string inside a Web view in Flutter. Above all, it will be easy to implement with dart, which is the primary language for flutter. We will use http library to talk with backend server. This library uses Future to return results. It will give us good control over what happens when we hit our backend.

As of now we don't have a particular merchant available for testing. The flow is as follows:

1. Create a merchant account in Paystack.
2. Provide test card numbers and CVV details to this merchant.
3. Use these merchant details to run the demo.
4. Replace the test details with your real ones after successful integration of this module into production app.
5. Deploy it on App Store and Play store to verify all the flow works as expected.
6. Once it is ready for release, deploy in Google Play. It will work fine.
7. At some point, if we need to upgrade or downgrade any card from Mastercard to Visa vice versa (which is not supported by Paystack). We will do this in backend by reactivating the payment method of the customer. This process requires our Flutter app to be running so that it can communicate with the backend. But when we send a request for that, we don't want it to crash the user's mobile wallet because that is why we have a dedicated Flutter module for this task.